Evidently, the form of the tail bound obtained using the Chernoff approach
 depends on the growth rate of the mgf.
 Naturally, in the study of the tail bounds the random variables are then
 classified in terms of their mgfs.
 The simplest type of behaviour is known as sub-Gaussian, which shall be
 motivated by deriving tail bounds for a Gaussian variables, say, X, such
 that 
\begin_inset Formula $X\sim N(\mu,\sigma^{2})$
\end_inset

, with density 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(X)=\frac{1}{\sigma\sqrt{2\pi}}\exp\left(-\frac{(X-\mu)^{2}}{2\sigma^{2}}\right)
\]

\end_inset

and thus, the mgf 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\E[\exp(\lambda X)]=\exp\left(\mu\lambda+\frac{\sigma^{2}\lambda^{2}}{2}\right),\quad\forall\lambda\in\R
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Example
\begin_inset Argument 2
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Gaussian tail bounds
\end_layout

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X\sim N(\mu,\sigma^{2})$
\end_inset

 be a Gaussian r.v., which has mgf 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\E[\exp(\lambda X)]=\exp\left(\mu\lambda+\frac{\sigma^{2}\lambda^{2}}{2}\right),\quad\forall\lambda\in\R
\]

\end_inset

substituting this into the optimising problem of the Chernoff bound, we
 get 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\inf_{\lambda\geq0}\{\log\E[\exp(\lambda(X-\mu))-\lambda t]\}=\inf_{\lambda\geq0}\left\{ \frac{\sigma^{2}\lambda^{2}}{2}-\lambda t\right\} =-\frac{t^{2}}{2\sigma^{2}}\label{eq: optms}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Therefore, we can conclude that any 
\begin_inset Formula $N(\mu,\sigma^{2})$
\end_inset

 r.v.
 satisfies the upper deviation inequality 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P[X\geq\mu+t]\leq\exp\left(-\frac{t^{2}}{2\sigma^{2}}\right)\label{eq: Sub-Gaussian TB}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
